definition.value: An amide of a carboxylic acid, having the structure RC(=O)NR2. The term is used as a suffix in systematic name formation to denote the -C(=O)NH2 group including its carbon atom.
The L-enantiomer of aldehydo-glucose.
The L-enantiomer of glucopyranose.

An aromatic ether that is the 2,4-dichlorophenyl ether of 3-aminopropan-1-ol in which the nitrogen is substituted by a methyl group and a prop-1-yn-3-yl group. A monoamine oxidase inhibitor, it was formerly used as an antidepressant.
A L-glucopyranose with an alpha-configuration at the anomeric position.
A L-glucopyranose with a beta-configuration at the anomeric position.
A dolichyl diphosphooligosaccharide compound consisting of a branched heptasaccharide attached to the dolichyl chain via a diphosphate linkage.

A diacetylchitobiosyldiphosphodolichol in which a heptamannosyl group consisting of one beta-D-mannosyl and six alpha-D-mannosyl residues is attached at an unspecified position to the diacetylchitobiosyldiphosphodolichol moiety.

A diacetylchitobiosyldiphosphodolichol in which an octamannosyl group consisting of one beta-D-mannosyl and seven alpha-D-mannosyl residues is attached at an unspecified position to the diacetylchitobiosyldiphosphodolichol moiety.
A dolichyl diphosphooligosaccharide intermediate involved in post-translational modification of proteins.
A polysaccharide derivative in which at least one hydroxy group has been phosphorylated. The phosphate group(s) may or may not be involved in the polymer linkages.
A member of the class of imidazoles that is 1H-imidazole in which the hydrogen attached to a nitrogen is replaced by a monochlorotrityl group.
A 7alpha,24-dihydroxycholesterol in which has S configuration at position 24.
A 3alpha,7alpha,12alpha-trihydroxy-5beta-cholestan-26-oyl-CoA in which the carbon at position 25 of the steroidal side chain has R configuration.
A 3alpha,7alpha,12alpha-trihydroxy-5beta-cholestan-26-oyl-CoA in which the carbon at position 25 of the steroidal side chain has S configuration.

A luteolin glucosiduronic acid that consists of luteolin substituted by a beta-D-glucopyranosyluronic acid-(1->2)-beta-D-glucopyranosiduronic acid group at position 7 and a beta-D-glucopyranosyluronic acid group at position 4' via glycosidic linkages.
The parent compound of the xanthone class consisting of xanthene bearing a single oxo substituent at position 9.
An anthocyanidin chloride that has luteolinidin as the cationic counterpart.
The erythro-isomer of  2,3,4-trihydroxybutanoic acid.
An erythronic acid in which the stereocentres at positions 2 and 3 both have R-configuration (the D-enantiomer).
A pentacyclic triterpenoid that is olean-12-en-28-oic acid substituted by a beta-hydroxy group at position 3.

A benzodiazepine that is 5H-dibenzo[b,e][1,4]diazepine substituted by a chloro group at position 8 and a 4-methylpiperazin-1-yl group at position 11. It is a second generation antipsychotic used in the treatment of psychiatric disorders like  schizophrenia.
A member of the class of methanopterins obtained by formal dehydrogenation at positions 5, 6, 7 and 8 of tetrahydromethanopterin. The parent of the class of methanopterins
The open chain form of glucose.
A memeber of the class of anthocyanin chlorides that has cyanidin 3-O-beta-D-galactoside  as the cationic counterpart.
A member of the class of cardenolides that is 5beta-card-20(22)-enolide which is substituted by hydroxy groups at the 3beta, 11alpha, and 14beta positions.

Any member of a diverse class of complex, multicyclic phytochemicals showing a variety of skeleton arrangements and bioactivities, and having in common a sesquiterpenoid structure including a lactone ring.
A compound which inhibits or antagonizes the biosynthesis or actions of proteases (endopeptidases).
A beta-D-glucan in which the glucose units are connected by (1->3) linkages.
